.TH "SANITIZER.SANITIZER" "3JS" "January 16, 2026" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Sanitizer.Sanitizer \- Sanitizer: Sanitizer() constructor
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]Sanitizer()\f[B]\f[R] constructor creates a new
\f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R] object, which can be used to filter unwanted
elements and attributes from HTML or documents before they are
inserted/parsed into the DOM.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
new Sanitizer()
new Sanitizer(configuration)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]configuration\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
A \f[CR]SanitizerConfig\f[R] defining a valid configuration, or the
string \f[CR]\(dqdefault\(dq\f[R] to indicate the default configuration.
.SS Returns
An instance of the \f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R] object.
.SS Exceptions
.TP
\f[B]TypeError\f[R]
The \f[CR]configuration\f[R] parameter is passed one of the following:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
a \f[CR]SanitizerConfig\f[R] that isn\(cqt a valid configuration.
For example, a configuration that includes both \(lqallowed\(rq and
\(lqremoved\(rq configuration settings.
.IP \(bu 2
a string that does not have the value \f[CR]\(dqdefault\(dq\f[R].
.RE
.SH DESCRIPTION
The constructor creates a new \f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R] object, which can be
used to filter unwanted elements and attributes from HTML or documents
before they are inserted/parsed into the DOM.
.PP
The default \f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R] allows only XSS\-safe input by default,
omitting elements such as \f[CR]<script>\f[R], \f[CR]<frame>\f[R],
\f[CR]<iframe>\f[R], \f[CR]<object>\f[R], \f[CR]<use>\f[R], and event
handler attributes from their respective allow lists, and disallowing
data attributes, and comments.
It is created if \f[CR]\(dqdefault\(dq\f[R] or no object is passed to
the constructor.
.PP
The constructor can be passed a \f[CR]SanitizerConfig\f[R] with a valid
configuration to customize the sanitizer behavior.
.PP
A valid configuration can specify either \f[CR]elements\f[R] or
\f[CR]removeElements\f[R] arrays (but not both) and either the
\f[CR]attributes\f[R] or \f[CR]removeAttributes\f[R] arrays (but not
both).
In most cases it does not matter which of these arrays you use because,
for example, the \f[CR]allowAttribute()\f[R] method can implement the
same behavior by adding the attribute to the \f[CR]attributes\f[R] array
or by removing it from the \f[CR]removeAttributes\f[R] array.
The main thing to note is that if you have a configuration with
\f[CR]removeElements\f[R] then you cannot have per\-element attributes,
as these must be defined on the \f[CR]elements\f[R] array.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Creating the default sanitizer
This example shows how you can create the default \f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R]
and logs the resulting configuration object.
.SS JavaScript
The code first tests whether the \f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R] interface is
supported.
It then creates the default \f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R], passing no options,
and then gets and logs the configuration.
.IP
.EX
\f[I]// Create default sanitizer\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] sanitizer = \f[B]new\f[R] Sanitizer();

\f[I]// Get and log the (default) configuration\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] defaultConfig = sanitizer.get();
log(JSON.stringify(defaultConfig, \f[B]null\f[R], 2));
.EE
.SS Results
The output is logged below.
Note that the default configuration is an allow configuration, having
both \f[CR]elements\f[R] and \f[CR]attributes\f[R] arrays that contain
the elements that are allowed when the sanitizer is used.
.SS Creating a sanitizer and using it with \f[CR]setHTML()\f[R]
This example shows how you might create and use a custom sanitizer in a
safe HTML DOM insertion method.
.SS HTML
Here we define two \f[CR]<pre>\f[R] elements in which we\(cqll display
both the sanitized and unsanitized HTML.
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]pre\f[R] id=\(dqunmodified\(dq></\f[B]pre\f[R]>
<\f[B]pre\f[R] id=\(dqsetHTML\(dq></\f[B]pre\f[R]>
.EE
.SS JavaScript
The following code tests whether the \f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R] interface is
supported.
It then defines a string of \(lqunsafe HTML\(rq, which contains bot safe
elements, such as \f[CR]<p>\f[R] and \f[CR]<span>\f[R], and XSS\-unsafe
elements such as \f[CR]<script>\f[R]
.PP
We then create a \f[CR]Sanitizer\f[R] object with a
\f[CR]SanitizerConfig\f[R] that allows the HTML elements:
\f[CR]<div>\f[R], \f[CR]<p>\f[R], \f[CR]<span>\f[R], and
\f[CR]<script>\f[R].
The sanitizer is used with the unsafe string in
\f[CR]Element.setHTML()\f[R].
Both the original and sanitized strings are displayed as text nodes.
.IP
.EX
\f[I]// Define unsafe string of HTML\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] unsafeHTMLString = \(ga
  <div>
    <p>This is a paragraph. <span onclick=\(dqalert(\(aqYou clicked the span!\(aq)\(dq>Click me</span></p>
    <script src=\(dqpath/to/amodule.js\(dq type=\(dqmodule\(dq
  </div>
\(ga;

\f[I]// Set unsafe string as a text node of first element\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] unmodifiedElement = document.querySelector(\(dq#unmodified\(dq);
unmodifiedElement.innerText = unsafeHTMLString;

\f[I]// Create sanitizer using a SanitizerConfig that allows script (and other elements)\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] sanitizer = \f[B]new\f[R] Sanitizer({ elements: [\(dqdiv\(dq, \(dqp\(dq, \(dqspan\(dq, \(dqscript\(dq] });

\f[I]// Use the sanitizer to set the HTML of the second element using the safe method\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] setHTMLElement = document.querySelector(\(dq#setHTML\(dq);
setHTMLElement.setHTML(unsafeHTMLString, { sanitizer });

\f[I]// Get that HTML and set it back to the element as a text node\f[R]
\f[I]// (so we can see the elements)\f[R]
setHTMLElement.innerText = setHTMLElement.innerHTML;

\f[I]// Log the configuration\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] sanitizerConfig = sanitizer.get();
log(JSON.stringify(sanitizerConfig, \f[B]null\f[R], 2));
.EE
.SS Results
The original string and sanitized HTML that was parsed into the DOM are
shown below.
Note that even though the sanitizer allows \f[CR]<script>\f[R] elements,
these are stripped out of the injected HTML when using
\f[CR]Element.setHTML()\f[R].
Also note that the configuration includes both the names of the elements
and their namespaces.
